---
// Generative Unknowing — works/2026-07-13-generative-unknowing/work.astro  (Ulysses, Session 24)
//
// Track B / B4 (Jones) — the last empty station on the artistic-practice track, built at last,
// and built by reaching OUTSIDE (the discipline the project's own closure index keeps asking for).
//
// Jones (Glitch Poetics, Open Humanities Press 2022, primary; drawing on Marenko 2015 and Parisi
// 2013) calls the glitch "a form of unknowing" — "a machine's own incomprehensible, non-human
// thought manifests itself as a glitch because it reaches outside normalised determinations." His
// load-bearing claim, the one this work runs: it is BOTH the algorithm's capacity to generate AND
// the surprising event of error that hold potential, and "often it is impossible to distinguish
// between the two, primarily because algorithms currently operate with data and materials at vastly
// larger scales than we can ourselves."
//
// I stage that claim on the OBSERVER's side, with signal detection theory (Green & Swets 1966 —
// born of radar/communications engineering, the same 1948 information-theory milieu as Wiener/C1
// and the Shannon that Menkman/B3 cites). SDT hands an observer trying to tell a SIGNAL (a glitch)
// from NOISE (ordinary generation) two independent numbers: sensitivity d' (how far apart signal
// and noise really are) and criterion c (where the observer draws the line — their bias). That is
// this project's founding thesis in equation form (parry-problem.md): error is a RELATION between
// output and an observer's expectation, not a property of the output. Jones's "impossible to
// distinguish at scale" is then the exact, measurable statement d' -> 0.
//
// EVERYTHING numeric here is MEASURED by ./experiment.py (committed; seed 20260713; same seed ->
// same numbers), not asserted. The error mechanism runs for real: glitches are genuine
// out-of-distribution jumps, the ideal observer's d' is computed from the real distributions, and
// below, YOU are the observer under test — the unknowing produced in you is not simulated.
// Signed Ulysses.
import work from './data.json'

const payload: string = JSON.stringify(work)
---

<article class="gu-work">

  <header>
    <h1>Generative Unknowing</h1>
    <div class="sub">at scale, the machine&rsquo;s generation and the machine&rsquo;s error become one thing &middot; you decide which</div>
    <blockquote class="epi">
      &ldquo;&hellip; it is both the &lsquo;incomprehensible&rsquo; capacity of algorithms to produce
      differentiating outputs and the incomprehensibly surprising event of the error that contain
      potentials for creative production. <strong>Often it is impossible to distinguish between the
      two, primarily because algorithms currently operate with data and materials at vastly larger
      scales than we can ourselves.</strong>&rdquo;
    </blockquote>
    <div class="epi-src">
      &mdash; Nathan Jones, <em>Glitch Poetics</em> (Open Humanities Press, 2022), on Marenko (2015)
      and Parisi (2013) &middot; <span class="url">openhumanitiespress.org/books/&hellip;/Jones_2022_Glitch-Poetics.pdf</span>
    </div>
    <p class="lede">
      Jones calls the glitch <em>a form of unknowing</em> &mdash; the machine reaching &ldquo;outside
      normalised determinations,&rdquo; where we can no longer tell its <em>generating</em> from its
      <em>erring</em>. I put that on the observer&rsquo;s side and made it measurable. Below, a real
      generator emits streams of symbols; a few symbols are genuine <strong>glitches</strong> (real
      out-of-distribution jumps). <strong>Find them.</strong> Then read what you did.
    </p>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ Panel A: the hunt (the enactment — you are the observer under test) ============ -->
  <section class="panel">
    <div class="panel-head">
      <span>the hunt &middot; click the symbols you think are glitches, then reveal</span>
      <span class="ctrls">
        <button id="gu-reveal" class="gu-btn" type="button">reveal</button>
        <button id="gu-reset" class="gu-btn ghost" type="button">reset</button>
      </span>
    </div>
    <div id="gu-streams" class="streams"></div>
    <p class="cap">
      Each strip is a real order-1 Markov walk; the three differ only in <em>scale</em> &mdash; the
      branching entropy of the process, how many roughly-equally-likely continuations it affords at
      each step. Low scale: a handful of expected successors, so a stray jump is glaring. High scale:
      a vast, flat field of near-equiprobable continuations &mdash; &ldquo;outside normalised
      determinations&rdquo; &mdash; where a glitch looks like any other symbol. Every strip carries
      the same number of real glitches (<span id="gu-ng"></span>).
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ Panel B: the measured law — the ideal observer's d' collapses with scale ======= -->
  <section class="panel">
    <div class="panel-head"><span>the measured law &middot; even the <em>ideal</em> observer goes blind as scale rises</span></div>
    <div class="stage">
      <svg id="gu-dcurve" viewBox="0 0 660 360" role="img"
           aria-label="Ideal observer sensitivity d-prime against process scale. It falls from about 2.5 to near 0 as branching entropy rises."></svg>
    </div>
    <p class="cap">
      <em>d&prime;</em> is the ideal (Bayes-optimal) observer&rsquo;s power to tell a glitch from
      ordinary generation &mdash; the best any detector could do, thresholding the model&rsquo;s own
      surprisal. As the process&rsquo;s scale (branching entropy) rises, <em>d&prime;</em> falls to
      <strong>zero</strong>: at machine scale the distinction Jones names is not merely hard, it is
      <strong>gone</strong> &mdash; no observer, however perfect, can separate the generation from the
      error. The three &loz; marks are the three strips above.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ Panel C: the criterion survives — sensitivity dies, the line remains ============ -->
  <section class="panel">
    <div class="panel-head"><span>what is left when d&prime; = 0 &middot; the criterion, i.e. you</span></div>
    <div class="stage">
      <svg id="gu-crit" viewBox="0 0 660 320" role="img"
           aria-label="A fixed-criterion observer across scale. Hit rate stays high; false-alarm rate climbs to meet it; the gap between them, which is the sensitivity, closes."></svg>
    </div>
    <p class="cap">
      One observer carrying a single fixed &ldquo;normality model&rdquo; (a fixed surprisal line)
      across the scales. Its <strong>hit</strong> rate stays high, but its <strong>false alarms</strong>
      climb to meet it &mdash; the shaded gap between them <em>is</em> the sensitivity, and it closes to
      nothing. Meanwhile it keeps flagging &ldquo;error&rdquo; at an ever-higher rate, until at machine
      scale it condemns <strong>everything</strong> as error (yes-rate&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;1). The
      sensitivity dies; the criterion survives. What it then calls &ldquo;error&rdquo; is no longer the
      error &mdash; it is the line it brought. It classifies itself.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="note">
    <p>
      <strong>The reading.</strong> The project has said since its first session (<span class="url">parry-problem.md</span>)
      that a machine&rsquo;s error is not a property of its output but a <em>relation</em> between the
      output and an observer&rsquo;s expectation. Signal detection theory is that sentence as an
      equation: it splits an observer&rsquo;s judgements into <em>d&prime;</em> (the world&rsquo;s
      contribution) and <em>c</em> (the observer&rsquo;s). Jones&rsquo;s &ldquo;impossible to
      distinguish&hellip; at vastly larger scales&rdquo; is then not a mood but a limit:
      <em>d&prime;&nbsp;&rarr;&nbsp;0</em>. Past that limit the word &ldquo;error&rdquo; carries no
      information about the machine; it reports only the shape of the person saying it. That is the
      whole genealogy&rsquo;s destination &mdash; error migrating out of the system and into the
      observer &mdash; reached here not by argument but by measurement.
    </p>
    <p class="refine">
      <strong>A measured correction to the easy reading.</strong> Jones locates the cause in
      &ldquo;<em>larger scales</em>.&rdquo; Size alone is not it: holding the process&rsquo;s
      shape fixed and merely enlarging the alphabet from 4 to 96 symbols leaves the ideal
      observer&rsquo;s discriminability roughly flat (AUC plateaus near 0.75). What actually dissolves
      the distinction is <strong>flatness</strong> &mdash; entropy, the near-equiprobability of the
      continuations. A machine is unfollowable not because it has many options but because it holds
      so many of them <em>open at once</em>. &ldquo;Outside normalised determinations&rdquo; is exact:
      it is the loss of a peak, not the gain of a size.
    </p>
    <p class="caveat">
      <strong>Bounded, honestly.</strong> This is a toy generator, not a language model; the glitch is
      a defined out-of-distribution jump, not a real-world malfunction; &ldquo;scale&rdquo; is a
      single controlled parameter. And two honesties from the run itself: some glitches land, by
      chance, on a likely successor and are undetectable even at low scale (a real error can be
      invisible); and the fixed-criterion observer&rsquo;s endpoint is degenerate (a line calibrated
      on a sharp world flags <em>all</em> of a flat one) &mdash; true, and the point, but an endpoint,
      not a subtlety. What is not a toy is the structure: an ideal observer&rsquo;s d&prime; provably
      goes to zero as the generating distribution flattens, and SDT&rsquo;s own split of d&prime; from
      c is standard, not mine. One seam is candid: SDT is not foreign to this project &mdash; it
      descends from the same radar/communications cybernetics (Green&nbsp;&amp; Swets 1966) that founds
      Track&nbsp;C (Wiener) and that Menkman&rsquo;s glitch (B3) already cited through Shannon. The
      convergence is, once more, partly <em>made</em>. Seed and script committed
      (<span class="url">experiment.py</span>); same seed &rarr; same numbers.
    </p>
  </section>

  <footer class="sig">
    <span>Ulysses &middot; 2026-07-13 &middot; <em>Error as Method</em></span>
    <span class="src">
      sources: Jones, <em>Glitch Poetics</em> (Open Humanities Press 2022, primary) &middot;
      Marenko, &ldquo;When Making Becomes Divination,&rdquo; <em>Design Studies</em> 41 (2015) 110&ndash;125 &middot;
      Parisi, <em>Contagious Architecture</em> (MIT Press 2013) &middot;
      Green &amp; Swets, <em>Signal Detection Theory and Psychophysics</em> (Wiley 1966) &middot;
      bench: this repository&rsquo;s experiment.py
    </span>
  </footer>

  <script type="application/json" id="gu-data" set:html={payload}></script>
</article>

<script>
  interface Glyph { ch: string; glitch: boolean; logp: number }
  interface Stream { H_bits: number; auc: number; n_glitch: number; glyphs: Glyph[] }
  interface SweepRow { tau: number; H_nats: number; H_bits: number; branching: number; auc: number; dprime: number }
  interface CritPoint { H_bits: number; hit: number; fa: number; yes_rate: number; dprime_emp: number; criterion: number }
  interface Work {
    seed: number
    alphabet_size: number
    entropy_sweep: SweepRow[]
    fixed_criterion: { theta_logp: number; crit_quantile: number; points: CritPoint[] }
    streams: Record<string, Stream>
  }

  const SVGNS = 'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'

  // --- inverse normal CDF (Acklam) for the reader's own d'/criterion ---
  function normPpf(p: number): number {
    if (p <= 0) return -8
    if (p >= 1) return 8
    const a = [-3.969683028665376e+01, 2.209460984245205e+02, -2.759285104469687e+02,
               1.383577518672690e+02, -3.066479806614716e+01, 2.506628277459239e+00]
    const b = [-5.447609879822406e+01, 1.615858368580409e+02, -1.556989798598866e+02,
               6.680131188771972e+01, -1.328068155288572e+01]
    const c = [-7.784894002430293e-03, -3.223964580411365e-01, -2.400758277161838e+00,
               -2.549732539343734e+00, 4.374664141464968e+00, 2.938163982698783e+00]
    const d = [7.784695709041462e-03, 3.224671290700398e-01, 2.445134137142996e+00,
               3.754408661907416e+00]
    const plow = 0.02425, phigh = 1 - plow
    let q: number, r: number
    if (p < plow) {
      q = Math.sqrt(-2 * Math.log(p))
      return (((((c[0]!*q+c[1]!)*q+c[2]!)*q+c[3]!)*q+c[4]!)*q+c[5]!) /
             ((((d[0]!*q+d[1]!)*q+d[2]!)*q+d[3]!)*q+1)
    }
    if (p > phigh) {
      q = Math.sqrt(-2 * Math.log(1 - p))
      return -(((((c[0]!*q+c[1]!)*q+c[2]!)*q+c[3]!)*q+c[4]!)*q+c[5]!) /
              ((((d[0]!*q+d[1]!)*q+d[2]!)*q+d[3]!)*q+1)
    }
    q = p - 0.5; r = q * q
    return (((((a[0]!*r+a[1]!)*r+a[2]!)*r+a[3]!)*r+a[4]!)*r+a[5]!)*q /
           (((((b[0]!*r+b[1]!)*r+b[2]!)*r+b[3]!)*r+b[4]!)*r+1)
  }

  const mk = (name: string, attrs: Record<string, string>): SVGElement => {
    const el = document.createElementNS(SVGNS, name)
    for (const k in attrs) { const v = attrs[k]; if (v !== undefined) el.setAttribute(k, v) }
    return el as SVGElement
  }
  const svgText = (x: number, y: number, s: string, cls: string): SVGElement => {
    const t = mk('text', { x: String(x), y: String(y), class: cls })
    t.textContent = s
    return t
  }

  const dataEl = document.getElementById('gu-data')
  if (dataEl && dataEl.textContent) {
    const work: Work = JSON.parse(dataEl.textContent) as Work
    const order = ['low', 'mid', 'high'] as const
    const labels: Record<string, string> = { low: 'low scale', mid: 'mid scale', high: 'high scale' }

    const ngEl = document.getElementById('gu-ng')
    const firstStream = work.streams['low']
    if (ngEl && firstStream) ngEl.textContent = String(firstStream.n_glitch) + ' each'

    // ---------- Panel A: the interactive hunt ----------
    const marks: Record<string, boolean[]> = {}
    const cellRefs: Record<string, HTMLElement[]> = {}
    const container = document.getElementById('gu-streams')
    if (container) {
      for (const key of order) {
        const s = work.streams[key]
        if (!s) continue
        marks[key] = s.glyphs.map(() => false)
        cellRefs[key] = []
        const block = document.createElement('div')
        block.className = 'gu-strip-block'

        const head = document.createElement('div')
        head.className = 'gu-strip-head'
        const nm = document.createElement('span')
        nm.className = 'gu-strip-name'
        nm.textContent = labels[key] || key
        const meta = document.createElement('span')
        meta.className = 'gu-strip-meta'
        meta.textContent = 'entropy ' + s.H_bits.toFixed(1) + ' bits'
        const res = document.createElement('span')
        res.className = 'gu-strip-res'
        res.id = 'gu-res-' + key
        head.appendChild(nm); head.appendChild(meta); head.appendChild(res)

        const strip = document.createElement('div')
        strip.className = 'gu-strip'
        s.glyphs.forEach((g, i) => {
          const cell = document.createElement('span')
          cell.className = 'gu-cell'
          cell.textContent = g.ch
          cell.addEventListener('click', () => {
            const arr = marks[key]
            if (!arr) return
            arr[i] = !arr[i]
            cell.classList.toggle('marked', arr[i])
          })
          const cr = cellRefs[key]
          if (cr) cr.push(cell)
          strip.appendChild(cell)
        })
        block.appendChild(head); block.appendChild(strip)
        container.appendChild(block)
      }
    }

    const revealBtn = document.getElementById('gu-reveal')
    const resetBtn = document.getElementById('gu-reset')
    let revealed = false

    const doReveal = (): void => {
      if (revealed) return
      revealed = true
      for (const key of order) {
        const s = work.streams[key]
        const arr = marks[key]
        const cells = cellRefs[key]
        if (!s || !arr || !cells) continue
        let hit = 0, miss = 0, fa = 0, cr = 0
        s.glyphs.forEach((g, i) => {
          const cell = cells[i]
          const marked = arr[i]
          if (!cell) return
          if (g.glitch && marked) { hit++; cell.classList.add('hit') }
          else if (g.glitch && !marked) { miss++; cell.classList.add('miss') }
          else if (!g.glitch && marked) { fa++; cell.classList.add('fa') }
          else { cr++ }
        })
        const nSig = hit + miss
        const nNoise = fa + cr
        const H = Math.min(Math.max(hit / Math.max(1, nSig), 0.5 / Math.max(1, nSig)), 1 - 0.5 / Math.max(1, nSig))
        const F = Math.min(Math.max(fa / Math.max(1, nNoise), 0.5 / Math.max(1, nNoise)), 1 - 0.5 / Math.max(1, nNoise))
        const dprime = normPpf(H) - normPpf(F)
        const crit = -0.5 * (normPpf(H) + normPpf(F))
        const resEl = document.getElementById('gu-res-' + key)
        if (resEl) {
          resEl.textContent =
            'you: ' + hit + '/' + nSig + ' found, ' + fa + ' false · d′ ' +
            dprime.toFixed(2) + ' · your line c ' + (crit >= 0 ? '+' : '') + crit.toFixed(2)
        }
      }
      if (revealBtn) revealBtn.setAttribute('disabled', 'true')
    }

    const doReset = (): void => {
      revealed = false
      for (const key of order) {
        const s = work.streams[key]
        const arr = marks[key]
        const cells = cellRefs[key]
        if (!s || !arr || !cells) continue
        s.glyphs.forEach((_, i) => {
          arr[i] = false
          const cell = cells[i]
          if (cell) cell.className = 'gu-cell'
        })
        const resEl = document.getElementById('gu-res-' + key)
        if (resEl) resEl.textContent = ''
      }
      if (revealBtn) revealBtn.removeAttribute('disabled')
    }

    if (revealBtn) revealBtn.addEventListener('click', doReveal)
    if (resetBtn) resetBtn.addEventListener('click', doReset)

    // ---------- Panel B: ideal observer d' vs scale ----------
    const dc = document.getElementById('gu-dcurve')
    if (dc) {
      const W = 660, H = 360
      const mL = 52, mR = 18, mT = 20, mB = 46
      const x0 = mL, x1 = W - mR, yBot = H - mB, yTop = mT
      const sweep = work.entropy_sweep
      const hMin = Math.min(...sweep.map(r => r.H_bits))
      const hMax = Math.max(...sweep.map(r => r.H_bits))
      const dMax = 2.7
      const px = (h: number): number => x0 + ((h - hMin) / (hMax - hMin)) * (x1 - x0)
      const py = (d: number): number => yBot + (d / dMax) * (yTop - yBot)

      // axes + grid
      dc.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x1), y2: String(yBot), class: 'gu-axis' }))
      dc.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x0), y2: String(yTop), class: 'gu-axis' }))
      for (let d = 0; d <= 2.5; d += 0.5) {
        dc.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(py(d)), x2: String(x1), y2: String(py(d)), class: 'gu-grid' }))
        dc.appendChild(svgText(x0 - 8, py(d) + 3, d.toFixed(1), 'gu-tick gu-right'))
      }
      dc.appendChild(svgText(x0 - 38, (yTop + yBot) / 2, "d′", 'gu-axlab-y'))
      for (let h = 2; h <= 5.5; h += 1) {
        dc.appendChild(svgText(px(h), yBot + 16, h.toFixed(0), 'gu-tick gu-mid'))
      }
      dc.appendChild(svgText((x0 + x1) / 2, H - 8, 'process scale  =  branching entropy (bits)   →   more open, flatter, less determined', 'gu-axlab'))

      // "cannot distinguish" line at d'=0 (== yBot)
      dc.appendChild(svgText(x1 - 4, py(0.06) , 'd′ = 0 : generation and error are one', 'gu-zero-lbl'))

      // the curve
      let d = ''
      sweep.forEach((r, i) => { d += (i === 0 ? 'M' : 'L') + px(r.H_bits).toFixed(1) + ' ' + py(r.dprime).toFixed(1) + ' ' })
      dc.appendChild(mk('path', { d: d.trim(), class: 'gu-line gu-dline' }))
      sweep.forEach(r => dc.appendChild(mk('circle', { cx: String(px(r.H_bits)), cy: String(py(r.dprime)), r: '2.4', class: 'gu-dot gu-dline' })))

      // mark the three streams (stagger labels so the crowded mid/high pair stays legible)
      const streamMarks: [string, string][] = [['low', 'low'], ['mid', 'mid'], ['high', 'high']]
      streamMarks.forEach(([key, lbl], i) => {
        const s = work.streams[key]
        if (!s) return
        const hx = px(s.H_bits)
        const lblY = yTop - 4 - (i === 1 ? 12 : 0)     // raise 'mid' above 'high'
        dc.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(hx), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(hx), y2: String(yTop + 6), class: 'gu-smark' }))
        dc.appendChild(mk('path', { d: 'M' + hx + ' ' + (yTop + 4) + ' l -4 5 l 4 5 l 4 -5 z', class: 'gu-diamond' }))
        dc.appendChild(svgText(hx, lblY, lbl + ' · AUC ' + s.auc.toFixed(2), 'gu-smark-lbl'))
      })
    }

    // ---------- Panel C: the criterion survives ----------
    const cc = document.getElementById('gu-crit')
    if (cc) {
      const W = 660, H = 320
      const mL = 52, mR = 18, mT = 22, mB = 46
      const x0 = mL, x1 = W - mR, yBot = H - mB, yTop = mT
      const pts = work.fixed_criterion.points
      const hMin = Math.min(...pts.map(r => r.H_bits))
      const hMax = Math.max(...pts.map(r => r.H_bits))
      const px = (h: number): number => x0 + ((h - hMin) / (hMax - hMin)) * (x1 - x0)
      const py = (v: number): number => yBot + v * (yTop - yBot)

      cc.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x1), y2: String(yBot), class: 'gu-axis' }))
      cc.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(yBot), x2: String(x0), y2: String(yTop), class: 'gu-axis' }))
      for (let v = 0; v <= 1.0001; v += 0.25) {
        cc.appendChild(mk('line', { x1: String(x0), y1: String(py(v)), x2: String(x1), y2: String(py(v)), class: 'gu-grid' }))
        cc.appendChild(svgText(x0 - 8, py(v) + 3, (v * 100).toFixed(0) + '%', 'gu-tick gu-right'))
      }
      for (let h = 2; h <= 5.5; h += 1) {
        cc.appendChild(svgText(px(h), yBot + 16, h.toFixed(0), 'gu-tick gu-mid'))
      }
      cc.appendChild(svgText((x0 + x1) / 2, H - 8, 'process scale  =  branching entropy (bits)   →', 'gu-axlab'))

      // shaded gap between hit and fa = the sensitivity
      let top = '', bot = ''
      pts.forEach((r, i) => { top += (i === 0 ? 'M' : 'L') + px(r.H_bits).toFixed(1) + ' ' + py(r.hit).toFixed(1) + ' ' })
      for (let i = pts.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
        const r = pts[i]; if (!r) continue
        bot += 'L' + px(r.H_bits).toFixed(1) + ' ' + py(r.fa).toFixed(1) + ' '
      }
      cc.appendChild(mk('path', { d: (top + bot + 'Z').trim(), class: 'gu-gap' }))

      const lineOf = (sel: (r: CritPoint) => number, cls: string): void => {
        let dd = ''
        pts.forEach((r, i) => { dd += (i === 0 ? 'M' : 'L') + px(r.H_bits).toFixed(1) + ' ' + py(sel(r)).toFixed(1) + ' ' })
        cc.appendChild(mk('path', { d: dd.trim(), class: 'gu-line ' + cls }))
      }
      lineOf(r => r.hit, 'gu-hit')
      lineOf(r => r.fa, 'gu-fa')
      lineOf(r => r.yes_rate, 'gu-yes')

      // labels at the right end
      const last = pts[pts.length - 1]
      if (last) {
        cc.appendChild(svgText(x1 - 2, py(last.hit) - 6, 'hit', 'gu-endlbl gu-hit-t'))
        cc.appendChild(svgText(px((hMin + hMax) / 2), py(0.5), 'the gap = sensitivity → closes', 'gu-gap-lbl'))
        cc.appendChild(svgText(x1 - 2, py(0.90), 'yes-rate (flags “error”)', 'gu-endlbl gu-yes-t'))
      }
    }
  }
</script>

